#How do you remove duplicates from a list while preserving order?

Converting to a set removes duplicates but loses order. 
To preserve order, use dict.fromkeys() (Python3.7+) or a seen-set approach.

nums = [3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9, 2, 6, 5, 3]

# Method 1: dict.fromkeys (preserves order, Python 3.7+)

unique = list(dict.fromkeys(nums))
print(unique) # [3, 1, 4, 5, 9, 2, 6]

# Method 2: seen set (also preserves order)

seen = set()
unique2 = [x for x in nums if not (x in seen or seen.add(x))]
print(unique2) # [3, 1, 4, 5, 9, 2, 6]

# Note: set(nums) removes duplicates but ORDER is NOT preserved
print(list(set(nums))) # order may differ

